					<marginalia_text>
						Ad argutum ingenium plus valet ipsa Ars Elenctica, cum Axiomatibus Beda[e]:
						dictis A[e]sopi, Diogenis, Aristippi: Epigrammatis Martialis, et Heiuodi:
						Satyris Persij, et Politicis Lipsij: Regulis 
					</marginalia_text>
					<person name="Bede"/>
					<person name="Aesop"/>
					<person name="Diogenes of Sinope"/>
					<person name="Aristippus"/>
					<person name="Martial"/>
					<person name="John Heywood"/>
					<person name="Persius"/>
					<person name="Lipsius"/>
					<book title="Axiomata philosophica Venerabilis Bedae"/>
					<book title="Persius' Satires"/>
					<book title="Politicorum sive Civilis doctrinae libri sex"/>					
				</position>
				<position book_orientation="180" place="tail">
					<marginalia_text>
						Stynna[e] breuissimè; Brocardicis Kauferi, et Damasi, pro, et Contra:
					</marginalia_text>
					<person name="Johannes de Stynna"/>
					<person name="Guilelmus Damasus"/>
					<book title="Speculator abbreviatus"/>
					<book title="Brocarda"/>
				</position>
				<position book_orientation="90" place="left_margin">
					<marginalia_text>
						Distinctionibus Bartholi. Singula ad vnguem, ad vnguem. Panis quotidianus.
					</marginalia_text>
					<person name="Bartolus de Saxoferrato"/>
					<book title="Distinctiones"/>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>
				It is more useful for the clever man to know the actual art of refutation, with the axioms of Bede,
				with the sayings of Aesop, of Diogenes, and of Aristippus; with the epigrams of Martial and Heywood;
				with the Satires of Persius, and the Politics of Lipsius; with the briefest rules of Stynna; with the legal
				maxims of Kaufer and Damasus, both for and against;	<!-- CG: I can't figure out who this Kaufer is. Specialist help needed. -->
				with the distinctions of Bartholus. Singular things to be memorized by heart. One's daily bread.
			</translation>
		</marginalia>

